In 1979, there were plenty of options around for listening to music on the go. But those that were lightweight and cheap were not in stereo. THIS was the major breakthrough of the Walkman. Letting the masses listen to cassettes in stereo in a lightweight affordable player.

Several problems needed to be corrected from previous version. The Pressman HAD a playback head. And it also had an amplifier, but not a stereo amp. And the TC-D5 was a portable stereo tape player, just a heavy and expensive one.

Ibuka's own book states that his order to his engineers was to take the Pressman, "strip out the recording circuit and the speaker, and replace them with a stereo amplifier." It seems overstated to call this "heavily modified". And externally, the TPS-L2 looked extremely similar to the TCM-600.

/* Production */ The critical aspect was smoke in the helmet, not smoke in the plane.  This is what nearly killed Yeager, and what the stuntman parachutist did not survive.

/* Plot */ The jet engine shutting down was a *planned* part of the 'zoom' flight profile for these NF-104 extreme altitude missions.  The engine shutting off was not what caused the ejection.  The air up there is way too thin for the jet engine to operate properly.  That part was well understood and planned.  The movie depicted inability to recover from the flat spin, which is what caused the need to eject.

This change is subtle, but important.  Previous wording is open to being interpreted that this is the first time this kind of thing has happened.  But it is FAR more likely that this has happened many times, and we've just never seen it before.  New wording conforms more closely to the latter.
